WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.001 --> 00:00:06.906
On the evening of March 10th, 2026, a family in Taiwan received a LINE message from their father.

00:00:06.906 --> 00:00:11.444
"I had a mountain incident. Please report for rescue." "Xi Luan Da Shan (西巒大山)."

00:00:11.444 --> 00:00:13.847
Then nothing. His phone went silent.

00:00:19.085 --> 00:00:20.687
This is the story of Mr. Wei (魏). 

00:00:20.787 --> 00:00:22.856
A retired man. A beginner hiker. 

00:00:22.989 --> 00:00:25.825
And a mountain that does not forgive mistakes.

00:00:25.925 --> 00:00:27.927
Mr. Wei retired just two years ago.

00:00:28.094 --> 00:00:30.530
Like many people in Taiwan, he was busy his whole life. 

00:00:30.764 --> 00:00:36.603
Work. Family. Responsibilities. After retirement, he finally found time for the mountains.

00:00:36.736 --> 00:00:39.472
He started hiking. He fell in love with it.

00:00:43.710 --> 00:00:48.815
At 3:35 in the morning, a security camera caught him leaving his home in Yuanlin (員林). 

00:00:49.082 --> 00:00:51.217
He rode his scooter toward the mountains.

00:00:52.152 --> 00:00:54.487
His destination: Xi Luan Da Mountain (西巒大山). 

00:00:54.754 --> 00:00:58.591
One of the Taiwan Hundred Peaks (台灣百岳) — over three thousand meters high.

00:00:59.526 --> 00:01:02.862
This mountain does not require a permit. Anyone can enter. 

00:01:03.129 --> 00:01:08.201
But the mountain does not care who you are. Every hiker must take their own responsibility.

00:01:08.334 --> 00:01:10.637
He told no one where he was going.

00:01:13.206 --> 00:01:17.110
When his family contacted us, I started with the usual questions.

00:01:17.243 --> 00:01:20.547
Hiking experience? He only started after retirement. 

00:01:20.713 --> 00:01:22.682
Offline map? Probably not. 

00:01:22.816 --> 00:01:25.618
 In fact — he had gotten lost on his previous hike. 

00:01:25.819 --> 00:01:29.155
 Headlamp? Unlikely. He always hiked light. 

00:01:29.389 --> 00:01:32.158
Emergency plan? None shared with family.

00:01:36.663 --> 00:01:39.766
The distress message said he had an incident in the mountains. 

00:01:39.866 --> 00:01:42.135
But it said nothing about where exactly. 

00:01:42.202 --> 00:01:46.239
No GPS coordinates. No landmark. No distance along the trail.

00:01:46.439 --> 00:01:47.607
Just the mountain name.

00:01:48.208 --> 00:01:50.176
That is a very large area.

00:01:54.981 --> 00:01:58.218
I had three scenarios. Injury on the main trail. 

00:01:58.651 --> 00:02:03.189
Got lost — and got late. Or got lost — and then had an accident.

00:02:03.523 --> 00:02:05.892
The cell phone tower data would tell me more. 

00:02:06.092 --> 00:02:07.760
But I did not have it yet.

00:02:09.095 --> 00:02:11.598
And the first 72 hours matter most.

00:02:12.665 --> 00:02:16.436
I woke up after three hours of sleep. And I went to search.

00:02:17.470 --> 00:02:22.542
On day two — 36 hours after his distress message — I arrived at the mountain.

00:02:25.778 --> 00:02:28.214
The official search teams were working the main trail. 

00:02:28.314 --> 00:02:30.717
I went to look at the other options.

00:02:34.687 --> 00:02:38.625
Mr. Wei had chatted with a friend the week before about this hike. 

00:02:38.992 --> 00:02:41.561
He also mentioned the old logging village (巒安堂). 

00:02:41.761 --> 00:02:45.498
The friend told him there was another trail entry from the village side. 

00:02:45.698 --> 00:02:47.800
 That conversation may have planted an idea — 

00:02:48.168 --> 00:02:51.471
to walk down by the forest road on the way back.

00:03:06.085 --> 00:03:11.591
Since official rescue were already on the main trail, I decided to give a chance to the idea

00:03:11.791 --> 00:03:18.264
that he had lost his way on the second part of the forest road, coming from the old village side.

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:26.839
I searched along the broken second half of the forest road, toward the ruins of the old village. 

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:30.243
Long. Remote. With many landslides.

00:03:44.023 --> 00:03:49.128
His scooter was found parked near the gate at kilometer 17 of Renlun Forest Road (人倫林道).

00:03:49.262 --> 00:03:52.065
Near that gate, there is a small memorial tower.

00:03:52.231 --> 00:03:57.804
It was built in 1961 to honour over 70 veterans who died building this road.

00:03:57.904 --> 00:04:01.407
  Their bones are still here, in the mountains.

00:04:03.776 --> 00:04:08.648
Beyond the gate, the road continues deeper. But it is no longer passable by vehicle.

00:04:09.282 --> 00:04:15.488
I walked this section myself. I passed several landslides and ruins of old working houses along the way. 

00:04:15.855 --> 00:04:19.392
The effort to build this route is almost impossible to imagine today.

00:04:40.213 --> 00:04:45.518
Construction of Renlun Forest Road (人倫林道) began in 1959, under the Republic of China government.

00:04:45.785 --> 00:04:50.123
By 1960, a full working village had been established deep in the forest.

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:55.795
At kilometer 37 — at 2600 meters elevation — Luan An Tang (巒安堂).

00:04:56.929 --> 00:04:58.498
Over one hundred people lived there.

00:04:58.631 --> 00:05:03.870
Offices. Dormitories. A small temple. A machine room. Electricity.

00:05:56.089 --> 00:05:58.491
And below the village — a greenhouse garden. 

00:05:58.691 --> 00:06:02.328
The only place in Taiwan at the time where peonies were grown. 

00:06:02.528 --> 00:06:04.430
Four hundred peony trees.

00:06:04.564 --> 00:06:09.135
The flowers were cut and sent directly to the President's wife, Soong May-ling (宋美齡).

00:06:12.839 --> 00:06:15.108
Even tourists used to come here by bus. 

00:06:15.241 --> 00:06:17.977
Now you can barely walk the road safely.

00:06:18.511 --> 00:06:23.649
The village sits at 2600 meters. The summit is only 500 meters higher. 

00:06:23.783 --> 00:06:28.755
That gives you an idea of how different this mountain felt from the eastern side.

00:06:28.855 --> 00:06:31.157
Today, all of it is ruins.

00:06:36.796 --> 00:06:42.401
I saw remains of gondola cables — the lifts that once moved logs down the mountain.

00:06:42.869 --> 00:06:44.370
And I saw something else. 

00:06:44.570 --> 00:06:48.274
A freshly cut block of wood. Clean cuts. Very recent. 

00:06:48.541 --> 00:06:54.714
This is the work of so-called Mountain Rats (山老鼠) — people who illegally remove timber from protected forests.

00:06:55.481 --> 00:06:56.716
It is prohibited now.

00:06:56.883 --> 00:07:02.655
But it is worth remembering: the logging companies themselves cut down enormous amounts of ancient trees.

00:07:02.855 --> 00:07:05.858
The Mountain Rats are taking what little is left.

00:07:08.461 --> 00:07:13.299
The old forest road is no longer used by hikers. All trail markers have been removed.

00:07:13.432 --> 00:07:19.372
Part of the road still serves one purpose — accessing a water source from the main river.

00:07:26.412 --> 00:07:29.182
There are actually three ways to reach Xi Luan Da Mountain (西巒大山). 

00:07:29.348 --> 00:07:33.553
The classic hiking trail from kilometer 17 of Renlun Forest Road (人倫林道). 

00:07:33.686 --> 00:07:39.425
Just over six kilometers. But it climbs from 1500 meters to 3081 meters. 

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:45.398
One thousand six hundred meters of elevation gain. Steep. Technical.

00:07:49.669 --> 00:07:53.706
The second route continues along this broken second half of Renlun Forest Road (人倫林道), 

00:07:53.806 --> 00:07:56.242
through the ruins of the old logging village (巒安堂). 

00:07:56.309 --> 00:07:59.412
This road is too damaged even for experienced hikers.

00:08:13.926 --> 00:08:17.497
The third route comes from the north — via Shuanglong Forest Road (雙龍林道). 

00:08:17.797 --> 00:08:22.635
A longer approach, usually with a night or two spent in the old village.

00:08:30.943 --> 00:08:34.180
Some hikers call Xi Luan Da Mountain (西巒大山) "weak-knee mountain."

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:40.219
After my first day of 27 kilometers — with 2250 meters of elevation gain  

00:08:40.386 --> 00:08:42.588
of searching, I understood why.

00:08:46.092 --> 00:08:48.294
By now I had the cell phone tower data.

00:08:48.561 --> 00:08:50.863
After 6:18 in the evening on March 10th,

00:08:50.897 --> 00:08:55.234
his phone lost signal from towers in the south — in the Alishan (阿里山) area. 

00:08:55.234 --> 00:08:59.305
But it was still connecting — weakly — from Puli (埔里) and Sun Moon Lake (日月潭) area. 

00:08:59.405 --> 00:09:05.211
And his last tower — on a peak called Jinlongshan (金龍山), which I know well from my gravel biking.

00:09:06.145 --> 00:09:09.448
These towers all have visibility to the north face of the mountain. 

00:09:09.615 --> 00:09:14.053
This told me something important. He had moved north of the main ridge.

00:09:17.957 --> 00:09:19.525
Around the 6-kilometer mark,

00:09:19.659 --> 00:09:25.264
it is easy to lose the trail. It will lead you down into the creek on the north side of the mountain.

00:09:25.431 --> 00:09:28.367
There is also something unique about this area right now. 

00:09:28.601 --> 00:09:34.640
The mountain bamboo — which normally makes off-trail movement almost impossible — had dried out completely.

00:09:34.974 --> 00:09:39.278
When bamboo dies across a whole slope, it opens up like a corridor.

00:09:39.545 --> 00:09:41.647
You can walk almost anywhere.

00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:47.053
That sounds like freedom. And for exploring, it is. 

00:09:47.386 --> 00:09:53.559
But it also means a lost hiker can wander very far, very fast, in completely random terrain. 

00:09:53.659 --> 00:09:58.998
No path. No reference. Just open forest — going down.

00:10:06.973 --> 00:10:12.645
I marked the creek on the north side as my hot zone. On day four, I went there.

00:10:13.179 --> 00:10:16.649
While I search — let me tell you what I think went wrong.

00:10:16.782 --> 00:10:20.686
Mr. Wei made choices that many hikers make. I am not here to blame him.

00:10:20.820 --> 00:10:24.190
But these lessons can save lives. Maybe even yours.

00:10:25.591 --> 00:10:32.131
First — tell someone where you are going. Exact plan. Trailhead name. Expected return time. 

00:10:32.231 --> 00:10:35.835
His family did not even know which mountain he was on.

00:10:37.336 --> 00:10:41.140
Second — learn how to send your GPS coordinates in an emergency. 

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:44.010
It is simple. Four decimal points is enough — something like 23.7130, 120.9082. 

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:47.513
That one message could have saved the search teams days. 

00:10:47.880 --> 00:10:52.818
Your phone already knows exactly where you are. The problem is — nobody else does.

00:10:54.186 --> 00:10:59.025
Third — always carry a headlamp. A real headlamp — not your phone as a torch. 

00:10:59.191 --> 00:11:04.163
A headlamp keeps your hands free on technical terrain. And it does not drain your phone battery. 

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:08.267
Also — your phone is your lifeline. Do not use it as a flashlight.

00:11:09.168 --> 00:11:11.904
Fourth — bring a power bank and a charging cable.

00:11:11.971 --> 00:11:14.407
A dead phone is a dead connection to the world. 

00:11:14.640 --> 00:11:19.478
I once forgot my cable at home. Carried a power bank all day for nothing.

00:11:19.745 --> 00:11:21.147
Do not be like me.

00:11:24.283 --> 00:11:26.052
Fifth — use an offline map. 

00:11:26.285 --> 00:11:29.955
Apps like GreenTracks (綠野遊蹤) or mapy.com work without any cell signal.

00:11:30.256 --> 00:11:36.395
Download the offline topo map for all of Taiwan before you go. It costs nothing. It takes five minutes.

00:11:36.696 --> 00:11:40.032
Then test it on an easy hike first — before you need it.

00:11:41.634 --> 00:11:44.236
Sixth — do not go in bad weather.

00:11:44.470 --> 00:11:47.406
The mountains are always there. They will wait for you.

00:11:49.775 --> 00:11:51.577
And one more thing I always recommend. 

00:11:51.777 --> 00:11:54.480
Carry a lighter. Or two, if you go overnight. 

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:57.483
Not for cigarettes. Not to make fire carelessly. 

00:11:57.650 --> 00:12:03.222
But in a true emergency — fire is warmth. Fire is a signal. Fire can save your life. 

00:12:03.422 --> 00:12:09.028
In over 40 SAR cases I have worked — no missing hiker has ever done this.

00:12:09.161 --> 00:12:10.496
Please think about it.

00:12:12.198 --> 00:12:15.367
And one last thing. Do not be shy to ask for help.

00:12:15.367 --> 00:12:20.506
Call 119 in Taiwan, or 112 — which works across all networks. 

00:12:20.506 --> 00:12:24.577
Do not wait until the last moment. Do not worry about being a burden.

00:12:24.577 --> 00:12:28.247
The people who answer that call — they want to help you.

00:12:34.653 --> 00:12:38.824
Day four. Thirty-three searchers. Volunteers and professional teams. 

00:12:39.158 --> 00:12:41.227
The mountain divided into zones.

00:12:42.995 --> 00:12:47.500
I worked independently — in my hot zones along the creek below the north slope.

00:12:49.034 --> 00:12:53.405
The creek had several smaller waterfalls, challenging even for me to climb.

00:12:53.606 --> 00:12:57.643
Along the creek — just steep walls and drops on every side.

00:12:59.712 --> 00:13:04.683
I was using the NetMonster app to compare my cell signal to his last known towers.

00:13:05.084 --> 00:13:08.053
Deeper in the creek, the signal really matched.

00:13:08.220 --> 00:13:12.725
But it may just have meant I was on the north face — the area was still huge.

00:13:36.715 --> 00:13:39.385
I searched the creek and the slopes all morning.

00:13:39.518 --> 00:13:46.492
I used my drone to look under deep waterfalls and sections I could not physically reach. Nothing suspicious.

00:13:47.560 --> 00:13:53.832
Then I decided to climb back up toward the 3.8-kilometer mark — near the old observation tower (瞭望台).

00:13:53.966 --> 00:13:58.571
I met another team near the ridge. They said they had heard a whistle below.

00:13:59.138 --> 00:14:02.141
Then I continued down alone and spotted a group below

00:14:02.341 --> 00:14:04.310
whistling and calling out his name.

00:14:06.245 --> 00:14:10.850
My heart started racing. I moved carefully through the terrain to get closer.

00:14:11.217 --> 00:14:15.921
Then a message from the family came through. These serach volunteers had found something.

00:14:16.222 --> 00:14:20.926
A black visor. Some snack wrappers. They belonged to Mr. Wei.

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:25.197
I joined the group. We kept going down, checking both sides of the creek.

00:14:25.197 --> 00:14:28.067
Petr : Petr. Beast Runner.

00:14:28.067 --> 00:14:30.269
Petr : But where is the hat?

00:14:30.269 --> 00:14:32.271
Searcher : You need to go down there.

00:14:34.473 --> 00:14:39.411
Searcher : The hat is right across from us, where that female team member is.

00:14:39.411 --> 00:14:42.414
Rescuer : Bypass high to reach that spot.
Petr:  Thanks, madam.

00:14:43.015 --> 00:14:46.669
But then I found something. Something that brought a small hope.

00:14:46.836 --> 00:14:53.008
An old forest road. Or rather — an old forest railway. Not recorded on any map.

00:14:54.994 --> 00:14:59.064
This kind of track was used during the logging era to move timber down the mountain.

00:14:59.365 --> 00:15:06.405
If Mr. Wei had been wandering here — disoriented, looking for a way out — he might have found this road.

00:15:08.007 --> 00:15:13.946
That gave me a little hope. He could still be alive. Even though the mountains were freezing overnight.

00:15:16.515 --> 00:15:20.819
The railway led horizontally — at the same elevation — toward the river on the east. 

00:15:21.153 --> 00:15:26.058
There were ruins of a working house. I went to the river and called out his name.

00:15:27.426 --> 00:15:28.627
Petr: Anyone there?

00:15:29.695 --> 00:15:30.896
No answer.

00:15:31.497 --> 00:15:33.065
I went back to the group.

00:15:33.499 --> 00:15:37.403
Meanwhile, two brave searchers(彰化特搜) had set ropes at the end of the creek

00:15:37.569 --> 00:15:40.572
and rappelled over the edge to look down.

00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:46.178
There — at the narrow base of a twenty-meter waterfall — they spotted Mr. Wei.

00:15:46.679 --> 00:15:47.880
He had not survived.

00:15:48.781 --> 00:15:51.850
The wall under the waterfall is over one hundred meters high.

00:15:52.017 --> 00:15:54.653
He fell twenty meters — onto the first ledge.

00:15:55.054 --> 00:15:59.391
Located two hundred fifty meters below the ridge with the main trail.

00:16:02.428 --> 00:16:09.034
The next day, the professional rescue teams used a SKED and ropes to lift him to the top of the waterfall.

00:16:09.201 --> 00:16:12.304
Then a helicopter brought him the rest of the way down.

00:16:13.105 --> 00:16:15.240
He came home. Back to his family.

00:16:19.345 --> 00:16:20.779
So what happened?

00:16:21.113 --> 00:16:23.949
He most likely got lost near the 3.8-kilometer mark. 

00:16:24.116 --> 00:16:28.988
There is a relatively flat, open forested area near the old observation tower (瞭望台). 

00:16:29.188 --> 00:16:33.392
It was getting dark. He had no headlamp. No light at all.

00:16:34.460 --> 00:16:38.731
After the examination, it appears he may have tried to call for help

00:16:38.964 --> 00:16:40.432
but the signal was poor. 

00:16:40.599 --> 00:16:46.405
If you are ever in serious trouble in the mountains — call 119 in Taiwan, or 112.

00:16:47.606 --> 00:16:51.543
He kept going downhill. That is the instinct — find a way out. 

00:16:51.810 --> 00:16:53.345
But that is always wrong. 

00:16:53.345 --> 00:16:59.218
On terrain like this, going downhill randomly almost always leads to a waterfall. Or a cliff.

00:16:59.551 --> 00:17:02.755
There is no safe way down except the trail you came from.

00:17:09.628 --> 00:17:14.600
His phone was found in the zipped pocket of his jacket. His bag still had food in it.

00:17:15.067 --> 00:17:18.470
The fall was fatal. And it happened that first night.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:22.941
This mountain is beautiful.

00:17:23.242 --> 00:17:29.448
People come here for a day hike to the summit. Or for two days — spending a night in the ruins of the old village.

00:17:29.615 --> 00:17:31.617
I understand why people come here.

00:17:32.484 --> 00:17:38.457
But the mountains do not care how fit you are, how early you started, or how determined you feel.

00:17:38.757 --> 00:17:41.660
You have to take responsibility. You have to prepare well.

00:17:41.894 --> 00:17:45.697
And sometimes — you have to give up. Turn back. Cancel the trip.

00:17:45.931 --> 00:17:49.535
That decision is not failure. That decision is wisdom.

00:17:49.835 --> 00:17:51.370
Mr. Wei loved hiking. 

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:54.773
He found something in these mountains after a lifetime of work.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:56.341
I respect that deeply.

00:17:57.209 --> 00:18:01.079
I hope his story helps the next hiker come home safely.

00:18:01.413 --> 00:18:05.451
The mountains will always be there. Be ready when you go.

